{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RAfH96ij1Npn9JdsGMcKsD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: query-layer-discipline\n     3→description: Keep reads in selectors/querysets and keep write logic in services without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Query Layer Discipline (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when introducing new read patterns.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `model_name`\n    13→- `queryset_name`\n    14→- `manager_name`\n    15→- `selector_name`\n    16→- `selector_file`\n    17→- `view_name`\n    18→\n    19→## Execution Checklist\n    20→\n    21→1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet.\n    22→2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager.\n    23→3. Define selector entrypoints for query composition.\n    24→4. Update views to consume selectors for reads.\n    25→5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code.\n    26→\n    27→## Guardrails\n    28→\n    29→- Avoid query logic scattered in views.\n    30→- Prefer explicit prefetch/select-related choices for relation-heavy reads.\n    31→- Keep selector naming stable and action-oriented.\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a83f5129-eb0f-4cb4-829d-d38e6c35c642","uuid":"2f2d1663-2a63-4d7d-97ae-224cc87dcdbb"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01222HnBVKEafPhkXYyKyb3L","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The SKILL.md file is benign — it's a documentation checklist with no executable code.\n\nHere is the query-layer-discipline checklist applied to your variables:\n\n## Query Layer Discipline — Plan for `Entity`\n\n**Variables**\n- model_name: `Entity`\n- queryset_name: `EntityQuerySet`\n- manager_name: `EntityManager`\n- selector_name: `select_active_entities`\n- selector_file: `selectors.py`\n- view_name: `entity_list`\n\n**Execution Checklist**\n\n1. **Chainable QuerySet** — Define `EntityQuerySet(models.QuerySet)` with chainable read helpers (e.g., `.active()`, `.with_related()`) on the `Entity` model. Each helper returns `self.filter(...)` so they compose.\n\n2. **Custom Manager** — Expose the queryset via `EntityManager = EntityManager.from_queryset(EntityQuerySet)` and attach as `objects = EntityManager()` on `Entity`.\n\n3. **Selector entrypoint** — In `selectors.py`, define `select_active_entities(...)` as the single read composition point. It calls `Entity.objects.active().with_related()` and applies explicit `select_related`/`prefetch_related` for relation-heavy reads.\n\n4. **View consumes selector** — `entity_list` imports and calls `select_active_entities(...)`. No `Entity.objects....` filter chains live in the view.\n\n5. **Writes stay in services** — Any create/update/delete and transactional logic for `Entity` remains in the service layer; selectors are read-only.\n\n**Guardrails to verify**\n- No `.filter(...)` / `.exclude(...)` chains in `entity_list`.\n- Selector name `select_active_entities` is action-oriented and stable.\n- Prefetch choices are explicit, not implicit N+1.\n\nLet me know which step you want to implement and I'll edit the relevant existing files."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":662,"cache_read_input_tokens":21662,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":662,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a83f5129-eb0f-4cb4-829d-d38e6c35c642","uuid":"a31d3ca8-3370-4963-a181-40d49342e804"}
